{
  "doc_id": "10173",
  "text": "The revealed high sequence similarity of 45S rDNA individual copies in allohexaploid A. belladonna leads to the suggestion that they originated from a single parent despite the location on all three sets of chromosome pairs. Previous studies showed, that in some cases supposedly uniparental rDNA inheritance has actually resulted from the intergenomic homogenization of parental 45S rDNA repeats [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Indeed, we demonstrated that 45S rDNA repeats of allotetraploid Nicotiana tabacum structurally differ from the rDNA variants of parental diploid species, N. sylvestris and N. tomentosiformis [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . However, the 45S rDNA loci have the same chromosomal location in N. tabacum and in the parental species [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . We have also detected that in N. tabacum, 45S rDNA repeats originating from the maternal diploid species N. sylvestris were nearly completely substituted by structurally rearranged rDNA of the paternal diploid N. tomentosiformis [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Later partial or complete conversion of parental 45S rDNA was reported for other alloploids of Nicotiana [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Based on these considerations, we suggest that in A. belladonna, similar to N. tabacum [CITATION_11] , the repeats of one parent were overwritten or substituted by rDNA of the second parent following the process of sequence conversion.",
